=='''Energy Efficiency Retrofit For Leon's Car Care Center'''==
[[Image:Leons 001.jpg|thumb|right|500px|'''Figure 1.''' Leon's Car Care Center General Manager Dale Warmuth.<br />(Photo by Charles Swanson)]] 

In June 2008 the [http://www.redwoodenergy.org Redwood Coast Energy Authority] (RCEA) completed a lighting retrofit for [http://www.leonsmufflers.com Leon's Car Care Center] to increase energy efficiency.  

=== Redwood Coast Energy Authority (RCEA) ===

The RCEA is a [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joint_Powers_Authority Joint Powers Authority] commissioned by seven local municipalities under contract with [http://www.pge.com/about/ Pacific Gas and Electric] (PG&E) company to promote regional energy efficiency.<ref>Redwood Coast Energy Authority. About RCEA: Governance. Accessed online November, 2009. 
http://www.redwoodenergy.org/ContentPage.asp?ContentID=92
</ref> The organization is funded through taxes collected by PG&E and the [http://www.cpuc.ca.gov/puc California Public Utilities Commission]. The RCEA also operates under a smaller contract with the [http://www.energy.gov/ US Department of Energy] to promote [[solar energy]] use.<ref>U.S. Department of Energy. Energy Sources: Solar. Accessed online November, 2009.  http://www.energy.gov/energysources/solar.htm
</ref><br /><br />
The [http://www.redwoodenergy.org/ContentPage.asp?ContentID=392 Redwood Coast Energy Watch] is a $1.6 million partnership program between the RCEA and PG&E.  Funded by the California Public Utilities Commission, [http://www.cpuc.ca.gov/cfaqs/publicgoodschargepgc.htm Public Goods Charge], the Redwood Coast Energy Watch is responsible for the energy efficiency upgrades at Leon's Car Care Center and other area businesses.

=== Leon's Electrical Demand === 

Leon's Car Care Center (Figure 1) is a family owned and operated business that has been in [http://maps.google.com/maps?q=Eureka+CA&oe=utf-8&rls=org.mozilla:en-US:official&client=firefox-a&um=1&ie=UTF-8&hq=&hnear=Eureka,+CA&gl=us&ei=KxgbS8DDDc7ZnAf9xaTRAw&sa=X&oi=geocode_result&ct=title&resnum=1&ved=0CAoQ8gEwAA Eureka, California] for over 48 years.  Since 1992, Leon's Car Care Center has been located in a steel I-beam shop with an attached wood frame office, built new to their specifications.  The building was designed to decrease reliance on electric light by utilizing windows in the upper reaches of the structure, allowing natural light to penetrate to the main shop area. <br />
Lighting accounts for 20% to 50% of the energy consumed by a commercial building.<ref>Energy consumption.(n.d.) In Wikipedia.  Retrieved November, 2009. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lighting#Energy_consumption</ref> Automotive repair requires the use of power tools and computerized diagnostic equipment in addition to sufficient lighting. Power tools consume more operational current than lights, but are used sporadically, while lights are on continuously. The shop is also equipped with eight vehicle lifts and two air compressors that run most of the power tools. [[Image:MH.jpg|thumb|left|'''Figure 2.'''<br />Metal Halide fixtures replaced by Leon's.]]
The shop was originally illuminated using 32 400 watt [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metal_halide_lamp High Intensity Discharge] (HID) metal halide lamps (Figure 2).<ref>Farmtek. ValuTek 400W Metal Halide Bay Light. Retrieved November, 2009. Permission pending. http://www.farmtek.com/farm/supplies/prod1%3Bft1_lighting_fixtures_bulbs-ft1_metal_halide_bay_fixtures%3Bpg105713.html
</ref> The metal halides were supplemented with wall mounted fluorescents for workbench lighting. The office  contains computers, fluorescent lighting, two climate control units, one cold soft drink vending machine, and a snack vending machine.<br /><br />

